{"text": "Gods Will Be Watching is a brutal and merciless point & click survival and choice game. The game deals with issues of time, history changes, parallel universes, ancient races, and, of course, the gods who \"watch\". Gods Will Be Watching has six chapters, each set on a separate scene. The player must correctly assess the situation and correctly allocate resources and actions. Each action spends one turn, during which the rest of the parameters deteriorate. For example, in the first chapter we take hostages, barricade ourselves in the room and try to have time to hack the data terminal before the local \"riot police\" storm us. The hostages must be kept in suspense, both by intimidating with words and kicks, and by calming them down. Having reached the limit, or vice versa, having completely relaxed, the hostage will run away. A preliminary shot in the leg solves the escape problem. Hacking can be accelerated by charging the hack, remembering to raise security. Negotiate with the police, controlling their movements, or bargain for several moves in exchange for a hostage. In general, it is not as difficult as it seems at first glance, until at the most inconvenient moment random intervenes and arranges another dirty trick. The security level goes to hell, the hack freezes, and the hostage gets nervous and can blow up and run away. Spend a turn on a conversation and increase chapter time and general risks? Or solve the security problem now and then shoot the panicked hostage? Or even give the neurotic to the police? There are several options, and each has its own pros and cons. The game offers many moral choices: sacrifice a partner to save yourself, kill a hostage to convince those who remain to tell the code, leave one to freeze to death so that the rest can reach the goal; beat, or even kill the child in front of the mother - all this can be done or not. And every choice can make it easier to achieve the goal. The main character is Abraham Burden, a born leader, gentleman, legend and just a man with steel balls. In each chapter, it is he who is responsible for managing the situation and people. The plot is revealed through rare conversations with partners and characters' lines. I would like to separately mention the partners themselves. They are extremely laconic, each can be characterized with just a few words, even in conversations they are limited to a couple of sentences. For example, in the third chapter there is a need to sacrifice one of the partners for the sake of an experiment in favor of overall survival. If I \"got used to\" Jack after the second chapter, then I did not mind the rest. But over and over again starting the chapter again, you start to empathize with the characters. After several attempts, there is a desire to pull out and save everyone. And now a faceless doctor or a convenient Donald for experiments becomes \"family\". After all, so much effort has been made, and you do it out of simple stubbornness and in spite of the randomness. Not this way. DLC! Additional, 7th chapter. 20 years later, yesterday's enemies have united and are going to \"save the galaxy.\" In terms of the amount of information about the world and characters, the add-on plugs the entire meager game into the belt. What, who, how, why - there are a lot of answers, the game unfolds. Great. Music organically complements each scene, setting the rhythm of what is happening. The crackle of the fire and the noise of the wind from Chapter 4 gives the simple pixel art volume, and the credibility of the situation. The sound of teeth being pulled out from the torture scene makes you uncomfortable fidgeting in your chair. Gods Will Be Watching is actually not a very friendly, sometimes even boring game. The first chapter is frankly boring, while the second one catches only with the question \"how will it end.\" This game has cruelty, a lot of swearing, murder, torture, cannibalism, difficult choices and, damn it, random. But, having provided a little credit of trust, starting over and over again, you plunge deeper and deeper. ", "voted_up": true, "early_access": false}
