{"text": "Will Glow the Wisp handles very bold and modern graphics, presented in a way that looks like an old arcade game. One great thing that really stands out is the vibrant colors this game features, along with the fluid particles that make up the walls and just about everything else in this game. The 2D landscape that the developers have put together isn't that artistic or interesting, but it's kept simple and very interesting, because it's all made up of moving particles. Another great thing about the graphics is that it is very clear, with different colors for different types of objects and objectives, it is something that is often overlooked but it is the key to a good game: clarity. Will Glow the Wisp runs a pretty upbeat and techy soundtrack. This technological sound only adds to the arcade experience and fits the game perfectly thanks to its up-in-your-face color scheme and pixelated look. The game scrolls through the songs from the soundtrack as you play, which has its advantages: you don't get bored of a song as easily as you would with games that only have one song for each level. When you move your character in Will Glow the Wisp it makes a sound. While this is fine, in the long run it appears to be one of the things you think about and then ask yourself, \"Is this really necessary?\" Will Glow the Wisp is a hell of a platformer. When you start playing this game, you are told that a controller is recommended. Oh boy, at that point you know there's a surprise waiting for you when you play with a keyboard. It's no secret that bullet hell platformers are tough and safe, the later levels of this game are tough but the starting levels are super easy. Will Glow the Wisp has different grades of difficulty in which he ranks the levels, starting in the \"baby\" category after which you play with the levels in \"child\" and so on with four categories in total. There are three characters: one green, one blue and the pink heart, each has their own style of play, strengths and weaknesses. Whether they are useful or not obviously depends on the player. While this game doesn't have a lot of mechanics besides moving and running, there is one mechanic that pops up. Will Glow the Wisp has no hard walls, as mentioned earlier, they are literally particles that you as a player can even move in between. This allows you to cut corners and survive situations where you would otherwise find yourself dead, even objects are made of these particles. - Simple but unique visual - Fun and immersive gameplay - Energetic soundtrack - Physics-based movement can be a hindrance - Mechanics not well explained - rather short 7 out of 10 ", "voted_up": true, "early_access": false}
