{"text": "After a nuclear war, 4000 people survived in \"arks\" (nuclear bunkers). They were in cryosleep, so-called caretakers were woken up if necessary to eliminate disturbances and problems. After centuries of cold sleep, a wake-up call woke all the residents of the Arche, except those from Arche01. The story is played in several times, which results in several main characters in the game: On the one hand, there is Donnie Freeman who, together with a senator, tries to find out what has become of Arche01. On the other hand, you play one of the two caretakers of Arche01 named Mia Howard. It is important to fathom the secret of Arche01 and not just that. Events roll over and a lot happens before you see the end. The reviews for the game usually begin with the words: A Telltale game without Telltale. You can largely agree with this, but with The Descendant you not only have to give one of the multiple choice answers, but also often look for objects that are necessary for a task. These cannot be collected beforehand, they only appear after you have been given the task. The tasks are pretty simple, this also applies to the puzzles. However, you can leave out some things or not do them. If that is the case, one does not die, but is punished in that some of the descendants (descendants) are \"switched off\" by the system because of resource diversion. The system is always evaluated at the end of an episode. The more mistakes you make or fail to accomplish tasks, the more offspring are sacrificed. Since there is only one game and the episodes cannot be restarted, the decisions and mistakes are final. The game went well and looked good too. The Unity engine used has been exhausted well. I played through the game with the X-Box One controller. If you want to get an insight into the story, you can try the first episode for free. I liked the story a lot and, to be honest, I don't understand the low Metacritic score at all. ", "voted_up": true, "early_access": false}
