{"text": "It is an arcade game that adopted the rule set \"Dungeons & Dragons Classic\" for TRPG from 1978. It is characterized by being able to venture into the classic worldview of \"Mistera\", and it is a classic rule, not the AD&D rule used in Baldus or Awinde, so the Dwarf and the Elf race themselves are class. However, there are 7 types of classes in the classic rule, but halfling is not implemented. It is interesting that you can see famous named NPCs (Synn or...) in \"Mistera\", and battle with monsters such as Rich and Beholder, which come to mind when D&D, in an arcade style. The game itself (expressed in graphics rather than thinking) follows the rules better than expected, and the dwarves have a strong saving throw, so the progression speed is slow for petrification or abnormal conditions. It can be used or the magic is memorized, and the number of times is increased by using the scroll that has been obtained, or if you use a shield with a protection spell against evil when dealing with an enemy with a \"evil\" tendency, it becomes harmless. Is faithfully implemented in an arcade style. However, as it is an arcade, there is a lot of difference from the actual TRPG. The inside of the cave is so dark that you cannot see the front. Fighter: I take a torch and take a closer look at the surroundings. Priest: I take the Morning Star and make a turn (...). GM: !!! This feeling is also an inevitable part of the arcade. ", "voted_up": true, "early_access": false}
