{"text": "So many open-world survival games have come out over the past five years that it has become very difficult to stand out against the backdrop of The Forest, The Long Dark, RUST, DayZ and Ark: Survival Evolved. Fortunately, the guys from Unknown Worlds Entertainment have found a solution to this problem and transferred the action of their new game Subnautica to a distant planet covered exclusively with water. There is no land on Aqua, so the player must explore the ocean floor and share it with the sea monsters, which in most cases are very inhospitable. How did you get here? Everything is very simple: the spaceship \"Aurora\", on which you were moving somewhere, crashed at the very beginning and all that was left of it was a huge pile of iron and a saving capsule, on which the player landed near the wreckage. If you look at Subnautica from above, it may seem that there is only one void and the sea surface everywhere, but once you dive under the water, an amazingly beautiful world of new discoveries and knowledge awaits you. At first, you will swim exclusively within the limits of the escape capsule, because it is your only base, but over time you will discover completely new depths, hiding intriguing secrets and the ability to build entire bases there. In your own capsule, you can create items of varying complexity and operate storage. Since the protagonist's inventory is limited, and you want to carry a lot of items, you have to choose what to focus on: resource extraction, food, water or gadgets. If you operate everything in moderation, then there will be no problems, but if you turn on greed just for a second, your inventory will be littered with all kinds of underwater trash. Unlike other games in this genre, Subnautica is a very understandable survival game. Thanks to its intuitiveness and clear interface, it manages to offer something new with each new dive. For example, after a couple of tens of minutes of wandering, you will think of creating a larger oxygen cylinder so that you can spend more time underwater. Then you will make a scanner, flippers, and so your character will acquire a number of interesting devices that will allow him to enter the destroyed ship and learn unexpected details of the story, which are presented very competently. And if you think that the ocean has nothing interesting to offer, you are very mistaken. The underwater world of Subnautica can easily become the most beautiful that you have ever seen. It consists of caves, corals, algae and fish, and the deeper you dive into it, the more dangerous and diverse it becomes. At a certain moment, it becomes scary to play, especially when night falls and your path is illuminated by the beam of a single lantern, and an unknown inhabitant of the depths rushes to the meeting. Well, at least death in the game does not mean defeat. It takes you back to the escape pod and leaves you without a random amount of inventory items. On the one hand, it's okay, so death can be used if you need to return to the base, and the path is not close. The only thing that can spoil the experience is the technical component. Despite the two years that Subnautica spent in Early Access, and then two more that have passed since the release on PC, the game manages to give an unstable picture, especially when you emerge from the water. Then the frame rate is practically zero. And on little things, FPS can sag in places. But most of all, the textures that appear before our eyes, which unexpectedly appear in the distance, are straining. Well, in the area of \u200b\u200b\"Aurora\" the hero tries to get stuck in the wreckage. *** In all other respects, Subnautica is probably the best survival game on the market (in my opinion). This is what makes it clear, accessible, as well as a sense of discovery. Getting something new, every time you want to move on, to conquer new depths of the ocean for yourself and strive to leave this wonderful place, because this is the final task of the player. Just to achieve it, you will have to spend more than a dozen hours. ", "voted_up": true, "early_access": false}
