{"text": "Based in Nordic medieval mythical times, The Elder Scrolls V: Skyrim is a beautifully crafted game. It revolves around the player, Dovahkiin, or Dragonborn, and their quest to get the Elder Scroll and defeat the dragons as they advance through the open world of Skyrim. There are many characters to encounter in the world and many different places as well. Using the power of magicka, weapons, friends, and even your voice, you can free the world of Skyrim and save the wonderful/dreadful characters in the world. +The game automatically sets graphics based on your setup +TONS of Steam Workshop items +Spend hours customizing your character +Open world with miles to explore +Excellent characters to interact with +Thieving from those who are more fortunate than you +Many places and dungeons to explore +Shouting your enemies to bits and pieces +Beautiful map and graphics +Many different mobs to befriend/kill +Bioshock plasmid-esque magic spells +Various weapons to use +Build your own home (With DLC) +Craft your own weapons +Snipe creatures miles away from the throat of the world -Less than excellent A.I. -Large wanted sum for petty crimes -Can't kill chickens without getting wanted -Taking an arrow to the knee -Paying large quantities of money to get out of jail -Difficult quests -Some of the battles are repetitive -Expensive DLC sure will take some coin from your pocket I would give this game around a 9.6/10. The game doesn't have much of a replayability factor story-wise, but it is fun to run around Skyrim and completely obliterate once-tough enemies with your leveled up weapons. The game itself is fairly long to complete, but there are DLCs that are like a whole different game. You can destroy vampires, build homes, and set sail to Solstheim, an island off the coast of Morrowind, another Elder Scrolls game setting. Luckily paid mods were removed for Skyrim, so I don't really have anything to complain about. Excellent game. ", "voted_up": true, "early_access": fa