{"text": "Almost. Here it is the single mum lynx. A beautiful homage to all mothers in a wonderfully implemented, authentic and emotional setting in the wilderness. Although the sounds of the lynx and the other animals are authentic and \"true to scale\" original, the occasional cackling of some birds sounds like the game looks like. Perhaps this is solely due to my lack of knowledge about vegetation. Be that as it may, the music is wonderfully melodic and promotes the feeling of an idyll, somewhere in the forest (or taiga) immensely. In terms of sound, the music starts the next foray for the boys, while the music never drowns out the noises of the forest and thus blurs everything into one another. Shelter 2 takes getting used to. Like the predecessor, the same - one might almost say graphic pulp - textures were used. Nevertheless, lynxes and are faithfully recreated in their own setting. Although the fur does not quite correspond to the animal that we all know, you can still see what it is supposed to represent. You can complain here, but you don't have to. The other animals also look real in their own graphic representation and in no way come across as mythical creatures. Although you could have gotten a lot more out of bushes and trees, you can recognize them as such after a while. Granted, some bushes look like the green ghost from GhostBusters (Slimy?). Shelter 2 relies on its own character that you have to like. Both the controls and the entire game mechanics rely on the simplest of the simplest. There is no complexity or variety in terms of control. Everything can be maneuvered using WASD, Shift (for the sprint), spacebar (jump) and mouse. There are smaller tutorials as an introduction, but they do not cover all functions. Can be seen as a negative point, but since you can count all functions on one hand, that's not so bad. Maybe there is also a plan to find out some things on your own. Thanks to steam workshops and especially the guides, there is help for all those who did not know Shelter 1 and therefore do not yet know what to do. The only change here is in the area of \u200b\u200bhunting. There is a smaller selection of prey that can be hunted in different ways. I don't need to explain in great detail, everyone will probably know that a rabbit is a short bite to eat in between, whereas it takes a little more than racing straight towards an elk (little tip: jumping!). In the end, however, everything fills you up and this review is also finished. Shelter 2 does its own thing and if you can excuse the graphics, it does it well. The game is a sure-fire success and explains itself all by itself, if necessary you can always go to the steam workshop that can provide information. + + + - - - Pack behavior in adult animals would certainly have given the game a lot. Possibly even a multiplayer that you would certainly have gotten well here, and the story could be a bit longer. ", "voted_up": true, "early_access": false}
