{"text": "There are still many topics that need to be \"digested\". One of them is totalitarian regimes, which still have to be defeated in the minds, although their policies and monuments disappear into the abyss of history every year. Black The Fall is a game about escape, not struggle. And that's probably why she's pretty depressed. More depressing than such Limbo, Inside or Little Nightmares, where the hero is sometimes able to give a fierce rebuff to enemies. Most of the time here is solving puzzles and they are really original. Most are the use of light and shadow: you shine rays, hide from video cameras, show the puppets of the mode where to go. Sometimes the shadows hide an unexpected danger, and sometimes they save and it is unknown in advance what this shadow means to you. And the shadows are also scary. Even if it's just the silhouette of an ordinary worker. In Black The Fall there is an atmosphere of decline, from which you can still take out the individual remnants of the old system - the objects, and the ideas, which apparently makes the protagonist. Cracked concrete walls, mysterious cars and, of course, the promotion of the \"right\" system - all this is disturbing and surprisingly diverse. What the game lacks is the unity of the atmosphere. The first third is the real Kafkaesque absurdity of socialism, which is not devoid of even the peculiar humor from which the hero escapes. Here is a concrete labyrinth with its strict rules, in which you doubt whether there is any other world (hello, the project \"Samosbor\"). And this part makes the best impression. Here are the original puzzles, and disturbing locations, and successful references to the regime of Nicolae Ceausescu. The second part consists of industrial landscapes and ruins, where the promised robot trailer appears in the trailers. And the puzzles here are no longer honest, many of them are based on timings. The moment with the ruined church in the middle of building a \"bright future\" (which is almost a business card of the game) is strong, but it is one. The third part tries to put pressure on realism and does it well. Let's be honest, we see such landscapes almost every day in sleeping areas. But it seems as if they are from another game. Go through Black The Fall is worth the time, but it's a game for once. But if you have Limbo, Inside or Little Nightmares, definitely Black The Fall should be in your collection. ", "voted_up": true, "early_access": false}
