{"text": "I keep coming back to Galactic Civilisations III for one reason - the mods. The base game is decent, and the in-game empires are interesting enough (and have told story over the different versions of GC), yet it is the Steam Workshop mod scene that keeps this game alive.  The prospect of being able to load up empires from Star Trek, Star Wars, Battlestar Galactica, Babylon 5, Stargate, etc. and have them fight it out for supremacy is just too much of a draw. What makes it even better is that the mods have full in-game styles, too. So you'll see the familiar shapes of an X-Wing in battle against TIE Fighters, or a Galaxy Class starship. It just works.  Compared to Endless Space 2, the game does lack an ongoing in-game narrative of sorts that unfolds as you play, with pop up missions that can lead to bigger things. It does attempt to offer in-game decision making of sorts, with 'moral' questions that will take your empire down benevolent, Pragmatic or malevolent paths. Each path giving your empire a benefit over the other. Likewise, the diplomatic system isn't as deep as I'd personally like, but suits a purpose.  Furthermore, the in-game size of the galaxy is seemingly hardcored against the specification of your PC. The game will not allow you to run a huge, heavily populated galaxy if you're lacking the RAM. There are times when even the large size galaxy feels small compared to other 4x games out there (such as Endless Space and Stellaris).  Yet despite all that no other game supports the mod community like GalCiv does, and it's for that reason alone I recommend getting this game when it is on sale with all the DLC. For more reviews, follow my curator: ", "voted_up": true, "early_access": false}
