{"text": "EDIT: For some reason I can't seem to be able to put my review under the Director's Cut version of this game so that the hours played would show correctly. The original version of this game I have only idled for 15 hours or so get the cards drop (which seemed to take forever by the way). In Director's Cut I have 210 hours, and this review is for the Director's Cut  . Maybe the best testimony I can give of Wasteland 2:Director's Cut is that it made me put in 210 hours in less than 6 weeks. Now I might have been a bit slow and thorough, but as you can tell by those hours the amount of content is huge. Maybe the first 20 hours or so I spent playing with my first crew which I then discarded, having learned enough of the mistakes I had made creating it. The rest of the time, 190 hours were divided between two complete playthroughs maybe by a ratio 100:90 respectively. It's not a flawless game and it may be easy to disagree on various amounts of it's design decisions. Nevertheless it certainly is a worthy effort in it's genre, and as a whole it captivated me like only a few percent of all games have done. If the post-apocalyptic theme appeals to you and/or you miss the classic isometric RPGs, I think you would be potentially denying yourself one heck of a ride by not giving this one at least a shot. ", "voted_up": true, "early_access": false}
