{"text": "Melancholy rotating its gigantic wheels, emitting clouds of smoke from huge nozzles, a miracle of technology, created by an unknown genius, rolled across the desert world, groaning. In the bowels of this steel monster, a tiny machinist in fancy red robes rushed back and forth, flipping switches and clicking buttons. Everything flew into the furnace, as long as the mechanical giant drove at least a few more kilometers ... This tiny machinist is you. And the steel miracle of engineering - the ocomotive - will rush you through the wasteland. Just be aware of throwing fuel into the crucible so that the flywheel rotates and the fiery motor does not interrupt its stroke. FAR: Lone Sails is a travel game. A meditative-contemplative game experiment, where there is almost nothing superfluous. Occasionally we make a forced stop to solve a simple puzzle or pick up a few crates of coal scattered around the area or whatever the gluttonous engine of our quirky steam locomotive is eating. What happens the rest of the time? And the rest of the time we ... go. We're just going forward. Through rain and thunderstorm, through a hurricane and strong wind, under the scorching sun and in the light of bright stars. Along the way, watching what happened to the outside world. A world in which there are no people ... During short stops, when we temporarily leave the womb of the ocomotive, we are free to explore the location a little, to look around. And an attentive player will be able to get some information about the cataclysm that shook the planet. However, the free spirit of the game is revealed when you throw a couple of boxes of coal into the furnace and again rush into the distance, on the way to nowhere. And if the wind blows it up, it\u2019s generally wonderful. When the locomotive picks up speed, we want to move the camera further away (the camera can be zoomed in and out to see small objects) and just look at the landscape sweeping in front of our eyes, at the open watercolor sky, albeit covered with gray clouds, or distant sunset mountains in crimson tones, but that's just behind our steam locomotive - like a small child. Either you run out of fuel, then let off steam, then look ahead from time to time so as not to fly somewhere. Our car does not stop day or night, our path is not interrupted. The whole game is like one big road. In moments like this, the game flourishes. The romance of a dying world awakens at the same time a feeling of anxiety and some kind of strange peace. Even in seeming moments of danger, this feeling does not leave. At a certain hour, the magic reaches its climax and a terrible thing happens - you don't want to see anyone at all: only you, the locomotive and the endless expanses stretching beyond the horizon. It becomes suspiciously, treacherously calm among the wreckage of cars and the skeletons of rusting dry cargo ships on the ocean shallow, among the meadows overgrown with weeds and wormwood and arid deserts, where there was once civilization and life was in full swing. Special thanks to the developers for not trying with all their might to stretch the gameplay. As soon as the authors understand that they cannot surprise the player with anything else, they hastily turn to the finish line. And I am ready to repeat what I said at the beginning - there is practically nothing superfluous in FAR, the game ends exactly where it should. Some players still complain that our voyage, you see, is too short. Dismiss! It's better to have 3 hours of extraordinary travel than a few hours of unbearable burden. Now I advise you to forget about what you just read and start FAR yourself. I cannot predict what emotions it will evoke in you, but in any case, it will be memorable hours and bright moments in its own way. ", "voted_up": true, "early_access": false}
