{"text": "The blizzard darkens your eyes. The speed of the wind is so wild that you forget your own thoughts and purely instinctively seek any shelter. Clouds of snow crunch under your feet, you trample over piles of people who have not been able to reach the thermal zone of the generator, curled up and lying dead almost in piles. You make your last breath, the steam is fleetingly carried away, and the reality is covered with frost. Frostpunk is a powerful game! I do not know about many, but she gave me certain emotions. And in particular - the emotion of hopelessness. Even if you manage to survive in this icy hell and save the city, at what cost will you achieve it? How many people will have to die for the benefit of the majority, and what neo-laws are you willing to accept to stay in power yourself? Are you a hero or a villain? What kind of person can you consider yourself after what you have done? These and many other questions are posed by Frostpunk. And as soon as you finish the very first game, an eerie feeling of helplessness will visit you. The realization that the story told here, in reality, may not be all that fantastic. ", "voted_up": true, "early_access": false}
