{"text": "EDIT: After going through a second playthrough, I have some added thoughts. I stand by the original review and it have not changed it or removed anything, but have added some final thoughts. Alright... Let's start with the negatives. There are a few. There are quite a few bugs, most of them minor annoyances (EDIT: See the end for how these minor annoyances became a lot more major.). But I have through one complete playthrough and well into the second one encountered two quest bugs that make it impossible to finish those quests. In the first case it was annoying, but didn't really ruin anything for me. The second one, however is a pretty big deal and almost causes me to turn on this game. I have decided not to continue with that playthrough until this is fixed. I should note that I had no problems at all with the same qeust on the first playthrough. This is not acceptable in a game that has had such a long ( and open) development time. There are minor technical issues here and there but I have not experienced anything bad. With that out of the way - This in an incredible game when it comes to story, plot, characters, atmosphere, lore and worldbuilding. It is well worthy of its claim as successor to Planescape: Torment. The protagonist is slightly less interesting than in P:T but the progression and decisions make up for it. There is an army of characters and quests, mostly very well done and varied. If you're not ready to read, and lots of, then this is NOT the game for you. The sheer amount of written dialogue and descriptions is staggering and very well done. If you're expecting action then, again, this game is NOT for you. There are few combat situations and most potential combat situations can be avoided through conversations and skills. It's a plus in my eyes but some may disagree. As a matter of fact there is no actual combat situation - it's referred to as Crisis and can be resolved in many ways, including but not limited to combat. The combat system is turn based and old-school gamers will be very familiar with the good and bad of such. I like it but it can be on the tough side. The character progression is fairly traditional and easy to learn but may not be for everyone. It's the ol' fashioned 'get a bunch of XP and level up' but with the added wrinkle that there are four levels / tier. You can only do so much every level but gain new abilities at every tier. The characters are pretty weak to begin with and get more versatile and powerful with time - no big surprises there. Long story short, this is a very good game worth the wait (I kickstarted it back in 2013) but it sure as hell isn't for everyone. It's an incredible world and story with a lot of great content but it absolutely will not appeal to those seeking a fast pace and/or action. This is a game that takes its time and rewards patience and immersion. That's my thing, may not be yours. But is sure isn't perfect. Finally (this will be a personal gripe, by all means stop reading if you're satisfied so far) I cannot, for the life of me, understand a looooooot of the other reviews for this game. I see an awful lot of complaints about the lack of action and combat and complaints about the amount of text. I don't mean to be rude, but it has been purdy clear from day one that this would never be a game drowning in action nor lacking in reading and lore. So I stress, again, if you're looking for action this just isn't the game for you. EDIT: I went through and finished a second playthrough. Using some player knowledge of the quests, I managed to completely avoid any such bugs and could do (and finish) all the quests. I still think this is a very well written and thought out game, story, plot etc. I also still think it will never appeal to everyone, but then people forget that nobody bought Planescape: Torment on release and it took years for people to understand what a remarkable game that was. In my personal instance, I alone in my group of friends bought and/or thought it was special. That's the good news. There's just no way around it, this is a buggy mess. I've lost count of the number of issues I've experienced but they've ranged from tiny annoyances to game-breaking in a sense. I had to effectively restart a playthrough from scratch becuase of a quest bug. Late game I had to relaod the same encounter repeatedly because my character was knocked down for -1 round, which so completely baffled the program that I was stuck. I've had a situation almost at the end of the game where I was basically stuck because I was given a 110% chance at succeeding at a task. But the thing about bugs is that they can be fixed and I have a feeling inXile could have really used a few more months, but wouldn't have dared to delay once again.  The positives of the game, as far as I'm concerned, still far outweigh the negatives. But I repeat once more that this game will never appeal to everyone. ", "voted_up": true, "early_access": false}
