{"text": "\"Brothers-a Tale of Two Sons\" In the description of the game in capital letters, white on blue, it says \"NOTE: THIS GAME REQUIRES A JOYSTICK\" should my gamepad be gathering dust on the shelf?) If you don't have the ability to play with a gamepad, download an emulator or play with keyboard, improvise! Also, the description indicated the presence of Russian subtitles. If you, like me, went into the settings to activate the subs, because you don't understand \"Japanese\", don't be angry bro! You are not alone. This is not Japanese at all, but a fictional gaming language. There are no subtitles, respectively. Let's move on to the game itself. She is a masterpiece. Drama is drama, from beginning to end. Not that everything is a complete depression, but most likely partial. We have two brothers to play. Some ailment struck their father and only a medicine located far away will cure him. Loving sons will do anything to save papa and begin their long journey. Probably, we all know the phrase \"Brother for Brother\"! The principle will be just like this almost throughout the passage. Only together. For the older brother - strength, for the younger - agility. While playing, we will watch how the younger brother struggles with his fears. The actions of the brothers speak of themselves. The younger one wants to frolic, the older one gets to the goal as soon as possible. In all locations there are benches, sitting down on which, we can focus on the environment. The variety of side quests will not let you get bored. The game is very similar to the JRR Tolkien universe. Most likely, the developers fed forces from Scandinavian myths. This game is like a good book that will forever remain in my and your hearts! ", "voted_up": true, "early_access": false}
{"text": "I had very high expectations for this title and I was severely disappointed by the final product so let me start by pointing out the issues before delving deeper into what the game does right. Right off the bat, after starting the game I was greeted by a gamebreaking bug that completely broke the scrolling for me (which mind you, is pretty much the entire gameplay). The text would randomly jump all over the place and the only way to keep it at the bottom (so I could select the dialog options) was pressing middle mouse bottom then holding the down arrow on the keyboard. I've tried different mice and the problem persisted. Also the game has no controller support (or at least the ones I had didn't work at all) and no option to run the game in borderless windowed mode. The main selling point of this game, which is the story, is done rather well for the most part with a few exceptions. The writing is excellent overall and the narrative is easy to follow up until the ending. The ending, while not terrible by any means, leaves a lot to be desired. There are only two endings and one of them makes absolutely no sense at all without understanding a minor detail that's not explicitly mentioned in the game (but is somewhat implied). Nevertheless, the consequences of your choice at the end is only left to your own imagination as the game abruptly ends there with no sense of closure or epilogue. The ending feels extremely rushed and incomplete, thus ruining the whole experience. Additionally, the \"Architects\" subplot and whole \"religious\" aspect of the game is done rather poorly and could certainly use some more work. There's not much to say about the gameplay, if you could call it that, since the entire game is just a series of dialog choices. It is a text-based adventure after all. The music accompanying the walls of text that are NOT voiced is rather boring and uninspired. The visuals are beautiful overall, although I feel like there's a bit too much post-processing going on that makes it look better than it actually is but that's just my personal opinion since I hate bloom and motion blur with a passion. - Artwork gallery - Excellent writing quality - Intriguing story with two endings - Interesting developer commentary - Appealing visuals and beautiful artwork - Ability to replay certain dialog sequences - Multiple choices and branching side stories - Great character design and development (with the exception of the protagonist) - Gameplay solely consists of dialog choices and some VERY light puzzles - No voice acting - Terrible puzzles - Extremely short - Confusing ending - Little to no replay value - Gamebreaking scrolling bug - No gamepad or controller support - No borderless windowed mode support - Monotonous soundtrack and poor audio quality overall  6.5/10 - Decent Subsurface Circular is by no means a masterpiece, far from it in fact as it has some glaring issues and a lot of room for improvement. It's nowhere even close to being a great game for that matter, but I do believe it can be worth the asking price for a certain niche group of gamers. If you're into text-based adventures with decent stories and branching paths, you should give this game a chance, especially if you can pick it up on a sale. ", "voted_up": true, "early_access": false}
