{"text": "Silver Chains produced by Cracked Heads Games and distributed by Headup brings a handful of scares and a melancholy soundtrack, The game starts with the character Peter, waking up in a Victorian era mansion, apparently abandoned, with no memory of how he got there. Like any good exploratory horror game, the simple setup and confidence in the amnesiac hero gradually let players understand the truth behind the strange mansion. It's a game about exploring a fetid-looking mansion with lots of empty space, hunting the next trigger that progresses in history and occasionally escaping an immortal enemy. With the volume turned up on your headphones late at night. Silver Chains features several sequences in which the player must hide from supernatural threats that hover over the old mansion. The game renounces traditional collectible items in favor of a good dose of memories, such as diary notes and old photographs that reveal the story and often present Peter's thoughts narrated to the player. In the beginning, players will have their first encounter with the most significant threat, the hideous, downcast matriarchal resident. Silver Chains has no combat. Instead, players will have to find places to hide or simply flee whenever they encounter an enemy inside the mansion. There are a small handful of puzzles, besides just looking for the right place to be at any given time, none of which is particularly memorable. After discovering a magic monocle, you can activate it to find the next access point, which ends up being the main tool of the game to progress in history, a functional decision, but without mechanical inspiration. In addition, several other unimaginative horror game mechanics appear - doors that don't open, except when they should, doors that can't even be interacted with, but that open for unexplained reasons later, random garbage in the way that prevents your game navigation as a force field and convenient blackouts that allow the player to be transported quickly to the next important scenario. Overall, the title does a good job of maintaining that cat-and-mouse dynamic as players progress through the mansion. it's a beautiful game, everything from the old, chipped paint on the walls to the scary and atmospheric sound effects that help to create a believable and gothic atmosphere. At best, he seems to be reading a Victorian-era novel, like Dracula, particularly, in the sequences where the player is faced with diary entries or excerpts of written text. Unfortunately, part of the game's delivery may seem discouraged or, at the very least, uninspired, specifically, in reference to some of Peter's lines in the game. Fortunately, it has more to do with its atmosphere and its reliance on classic survival horror games, which make the game really shine. Some of the ghostly scares presented are certainly decent and, as there is usually only one right way to go, Silver Chains can taste some scares that she knows you will be experiencing. Still, much of the game is firmly on track, wasting the potential opportunity to explore a home and thus giving players some leeway on what they will find and when. The game doesn't do much in terms of new ideas or concepts; however, what it does, it does well, but during my gameplay I couldn't help comparing it with other titles of the same genre. What I mean by that, is that it will probably attract only a niche audience, those who like slower paced games, where seeing is often more important than doing. One of the most attractive aspects for me in games of the genre is the ability to explore and engage with things across the game world. Unfortunately, despite a strong and well-realized scenario, it rarely presents branched paths or optional areas. In fact, most of the game world is static, which means that players can only interact with specific objects, usually those associated with progression. Silver Chains is a game that I recommend to anyone who likes horror and exploration games. The game is best played in short bursts, for a few nights with a good pair of headphones. those looking for a game that revolutionizes the horror genre or offers something new, may be disappointed by their familiarity with existing and well-established horror games. Curatorial analysis ", "voted_up": true, "early_access": false}
{"text": "Battlefleet Gothic: Armada. First things first, do I recommend it? Wholeheartedly yes! Now that's out of the way, on to my thoughts about this game. I will be say that I've decided to base my review on the feel and atmosphere of this game, it's faithfulness to the feel of the Warhammer 40k universe, especially with an eye to past 40k games. I won't be reviewing it on the gameplay in depth simply because I do not play enough RTSes to feel qualified to make an assessment either way. Is this game faithful to the 40k universe? Very much so I feel. One of the most striking things personally was listening to the soundtrack, the background music, the dialogue, and finding a welcome familiarity about it. It's as if the people in charge of the music at Tindalos Interactive had sat down to listen to all of Dawn of War II's music and dialogue. Some of those ship captains sound like they could be voiced by the Lord General in DoW2: Retribution. The music, with long mournful organ notes and soaring choral performances, is eerily reminiscent of DoW2: Retribution too. This helps the game feel a strong connection with previous 40k titles from Relic. Set against the backdrop of the 12th Black Crusade, the story thrusts you into a pivotal role in fighting against the various enemies of mankind. The weight of expectations lends a tension to each mission, even though mission types are picked from a standardised set. Despite that you do feel a sense of progression and each battle feels unique. The levelling up of ships and your admiral, and the amount of combinations for ship builds, gives you that additional sense of progression, and the motivation to want to win every single battle. Add in epic clashes involving ships of tremendous infamy such as the Terminus Est, and you feel a firm sense that you're right at the heart of the 12th Black Crusade.  I personally also love the difficulty scaling. I think it's perfect. Easy is just about right for casual players like me, normal is challenging, and hard and heroic are perfect for those who're bored easily if they're not juggling 9 chainsaws on fire. Something for everyone, just the way inclusive gaming should be. Conclusion: for any 40k fan who's been bemoaning the lack of any serious 40k titles over the last few years, this is the answer to your prayers to the God-Emperor/Ruinous Powers/Gork & Mork/Greater Good or whoever it is you pray to... heretic. I would recommend it even at its full price, and I hope that more content is to come. The foundations are there for this to be the big spiritual successor to DoW2, and I hope Tindalos Interactive seizes that opportunity with both hands! ", "voted_up": true, "early_access": false}
