{"text": "After reading overwhelmingly positive reviews, and loving games of this style such as Sherlock Holmes Crimes & Punishments (which I still contend is the greatest detective game ever), I was certain I'd love Return of the Obra Dinn so I picked it up on a 25% off sale.   I kept reading in reviews how this game makes you feel like a genius like no other game has.  That's right up my alley.  Unfortunately those moments were all too rare in my time with the game.  Even when I did puzzle something together it seemed fairly obvious, and on the flip side of that coin, there were far too many times when I had seemingly exhausted all my options and had to turn to guides for a nudge in the right direction.  Even then, when learning the correct answer and reverse engineering how that conclusion was made, it didn't make a lot of sense.   Far too many times I resorted to plugging random names/fates together in hopes of a match.  And while I did successfully identify several people and their fates in this manner, that does absolutely nothing to make one feel like they actually solved the puzzle, and yet in a few of the guides I read, apparently there is some guesswork expected here, that's part of the design.  I don't think guessing until you're finally right is what a detective game is supposed to be about.  Trial and error is not only boring but it does nothing to make the player feel like their observation and deduction is what made the difference.   I also felt like the grainy, old school graphical style detracted from the game.  This is a game about paying attention to details, and yet details were sometimes hard to make out because of the poor visual fidelity.   The UI was also very un-intuitive.  Flipping between pages of the book never seemed to come natural.  Sometimes Q would take you directly to the table of contents.  Sometimes it did nothing because you have to hit escape first.  Sometimes escape would close the book altogether when you just wanted to close that particular page so that Q would take you to the table of contents.  It's like each button had a different function depending on the particular section of the book you were in.  I'm sure this was user error but flipping through a book shouldn't be too difficult to program so that your buttons perform the same function regardless of your place in the book. The beginning of the game doesn't give much tutorial as to what things do.  For example sometimes when examining a corpse a stream of fog would come out of my compass and lead me to a certain spot on the ship.  I still have no idea why this would happen or what I was supposed to do with it because the game never tells you. In other parts there were seemingly nonsensical solutions.  For example in one scene  the ship is attacked by  All in all I'm disappointed that I bought the game and yet it's too late for a refund.  I liked the idea, and I love games of this genre, and there were parts that I did like, but all in all it was a letdown so I can't recommend it. ", "voted_up": false, "early_access": false}
