{"text": "Oniken presents us with a game with a retro aesthetic that will be sublime for those of us who delight in the 8-bit graphics of our beloved NES games, those to which we give away so many hours of our childhood. Unfortunately, the game is just that, an endearing graphic and sound tribute to those games, because at the end of the day the result is too difficult and unfair a game, which punishes you for everything. It is not just about memorizing the attack patterns of minor enemies or the location of this or that trap that will make you lose all the progress of the level, regardless of the merits you have done until the previous second, but you must also deal with the randomness of the attack patterns of the main enemies (bosses), some pain in the @ss in full rule, and the difficulty curve is geometric as the screens are followed, one after another. There is no sense of progression in your skills or anything like it, you pass the level without knowing what you did well or badly, out of sheer good fortune and that is not fun at all, in fact it is incredibly frustrating, this together with a control deficient that does not respond as it should in a game made to have surgeon precision is undoubtedly the greatest burden that Oniken presents us. I have left it halfway, because I simply do not have the interest to continue playing it, it is a pity because it looks good, but only good looking is not lived, you have to do other merits and those merits are scarce Oniken everywhere. An additional fact, quite worrying. The game executable triggers my PC's virus protection alarms. It could well be a false positive, the truth is that I have not the slightest interest in finding out. Uninstalled. Final note: 4/10 (Good intentions and nothing more). ", "voted_up": false, "early_access": false}
