{"text": "*THIS REVIEW CONTAINS SPOILERS*  The Walking Dead: Michonne is a fast paced game that covers Michonne's adventures between issues #126 and #139 of the comic book with these three short episodes. Visually, the game looks good, keeping the trademark comic book style that the previous Telltale series employed. Art direction in the menus and intros is particularly well presented, it's really stylish and has some nice nods to the comic. Unfortunately, whilst the overall graphics hold up to previous Walking Dead games, the animation can be a bit weird sometimes. Occasionally the characters move really weird sometimes, which can really ruin the experience you're getting. There are a lot of quick time events in this game, you'll be seeing plenty of them. There's quite a lot of combat, with slow motion scenes to show off Michonne's brutal fighting style. It looks cool but it really doesn't fit well with the realistic vibes the other games pushed.  The real reason why I don't recommend this game is because compared to the other TWD games, this game's story is pretty weak and it doesn't really offer much to the table, and it's here that the game's a letdown. The situations and locations that Michonne finds herself in are nothing we haven't seen before. Caring about these new characters is a real problem. They're all new, and there's a lot of them. There's just not enough time in this short series to invest or care about them much. The main villains, for example, are incredibly boring and generic, though the game does use them to provoke certain reactions, and that's it. The lack of character depth really affects the core of Telltale's games, like difficult life or death decisions. It's hard to feel much tension in these situations when you're dealing with characters you've only just met, and we already know that Michonne survives to continue the story in the comics.  Previous Walking Dead games did a much better job with their characters, because they were originally created for the game. They weren't in the comics so we never knew what would happen to them. It built tension and made your choices more impactful, for you and for other characters as well. With Michonne that's not the case.  For example, there is a choice in the first episode's opening scene where Michonne can pull the trigger or lower the gun. This makes the choice absolute pointless, since I mentioned above, we know Michonne survives in the comics so, what's the point of giving this choice? I guess they just can. And that's not the only problem. Throughout the game, Michonne tries to keep dealing with the loss of her daughters and hallucinates them. As a comic book reader, I appriciated the fact that we get to see the story behind Michonne's daughters mystery, since the comic didn't really focus too much on them. What started as an interesting plot point, turned out to be an annoyance. Her daughter's ghostly figures appear to her in the real world. It's supposed to be creepy but it's not, they even use those creepy child voices and jump scare horror screeches that you've seen a thousand times before. Michonne also experiences playable flashbacks where she's back at start of the zombie outbreak. For example, in the last episode the house is on fire, and you're trying to get out of there as quick as you can. Then Michonne just keep hallucinating her daughters for no reason. Over and over and over again. It gets pretty repetitive and annoying at times, though the last scene between Michonne and her daughters is quite emotional. Like I told you, it started intersting, but these tropes all get old quickly and don't teach us anything new about the character. Although there's sometimes a glimmer of real feeling, the overall approach is so clich\u00e9d and heavy handed it undermines any sense of empathy you should be feeling for her.  So, Walking Dead: Michonne is a medicore game and there's not really anything new here. The gameplay isn't that engaging because the choices don't feel like they matter as much as usual, and it's really disappointing to see no new ideas, especially as Telltale's last series, Tales From the Borderlands, added a bunch of variety. Is it the worst Telltale game? Hell no! (*cough Minecraft Story Mode *cough*) but it leaves a lot to be desired. Newcomers to the Walking Dead games may find this mini-series ok, but fans of the previous series will surely be disappointed with this game, like I did. ", "voted_up": false, "early_access": false}
