{"text": "What is CStW? This is a parody (if you can call it that) of the JRPG. The characters are joking; among the monsters there are many funny ones, like punk, dolls, etc. instead of consumables in dressers, we find funny objects and books, or rather their descriptions. But if for the first half hour you still find it more Cute than Funny, then then all this does not cause any emotions. The combat system is typical JRPG, but a bit simplistic. For example: was the character poisoned or died? After the battle, everyone will be healthy, except that mana is not restored entirely (in principle, there are no consumables, except for potions that can only be found). You can save at any time, anywhere, or even teleport to the city. But as for a parody, the battles are still not the fastest and there are many of them. As a result, you don't get pleasure from thoughtful and interesting combat, but you still have to fight a lot in random encounters, which is tiring. But the number of random battles is limited for each location, but there are still a lot of them. They either end at the end of the location itself, or stand and farm them for half an hour. The game also has \"Developer Comments\", which I called \"Justifiers\". You come to the question mark, and in 90% of the developer says how difficult it was to do this and that, so he took a simplified path, or did not do what he planned at all. (Really funny, huh?) The interface causes inconvenience in moments, although it would seem that the JRPG has more than 30 years of history. Of the advantages, I note the price, music and duration. True, for me the latter is more likely a minus, and for some reason it turned out 2-3 times longer than the others. There are also bonus modes for those who were not enough: passing without partners, easy passing at once with a high level, and passing for a partner Cthulhu, where everything is the same, only different dialogues and new characters. Bottom line: it was not funny to me, it was protracted, the elaboration of the world and the plot corresponds to the price, which does not really fit with the previous point. You can spend time on more worthy projects ", "voted_up": false, "early_access": false}
