{"text": "Yonder: It was on my radar even before The Cloud Catcher Chronicles came out. Of course, I had to try this relaxing game in which you don't fight anything with free exploration. But I'm sorry ... I'd like to recommend this game to everyone, but unfortunately I'm having a hard time. Let me briefly explain why I do not recommend such a sweet, nice-looking game. First of all, nice graphics, fun gameplay and controls await us when we enter the area called Gemea. This makes us very hopeful for the progress of the game. We also have many possibilities here, such as resource gathering, crafting system, changing our clothes and appearance, which we are familiar with from many survival games. Even the crafting system is very successful. We can produce many tools in 8 different categories (Wayfarer, Chef, Carpenter, Constructor, Tinker, Brewer, Tailor, Master). However, this whole system is not very necessary for you to finish the main task. Needed for side missions. There are many regions in Gamea and each region has its own quests, happiness rate and collectibles. It is also covered with a layer of cloud (we can call it a curse) that limits our access in most places. In order to reach these places, we need to collect sweet creatures related to the main task. They are also hidden on the whole map. Some open up with few creatures, while others want more. That's why we have to wander. Apart from these, places where we can do agriculture have been added to the regions. If we want, we can feed animals, grow plant and tree species, and produce some raw materials. Do not expect a very detailed system. It is okay if you never do. But you definitely need to build the agricultural area. Why you might say it: Fast travel is done only at certain points and on the farms you open with an item you can produce. So why is it necessary? Although the game allows free roaming, it is often torture to move from one point to another. Although the map looks good, it was designed as a disgrace. Reaching a point you see is often blocked by huge mountains and deep waters. Of course, we couldn't expect him to say \"come here right now\", but almost everywhere is like this. The game forces the mountains to climb the slopes by taking ziblock steps to go on a mission that is right at your foot. This sooner or later haunts you. Fast travel points are also in very ridiculous places, so after a while you get colder from the game. I said the controls are nice. In general yes it is, but there is a huge problem with jumping. We said that your departure on duty is already disabled with mountains and slopes. Well, you might think, let me shorten the way to some climbable points. At this point you need to jump. And this is deliberately designed to be disgusting. For example, there is a small slope in front of you and you plan to jump up. If the character is adjacent to that cliff, it instantly throws you back when you want to jump forward. It does not jump right at the bottom and cannot reach from afar. Most of the time you want to jump you fall lower. It's an Alt + F4 case. Although the graphics look beautiful, the day-night cycle, and the lighting are nice, these troubles are making your enthusiasm for most of the game. The fun drops the number of floors and in the end it remains a very mediocre game. The main task can be completed in a very short time. A different fun process could be found in a game that fell on that much crafting system. But you can finish the game without learning most things. I did that. After seeing the troubles I played with the logic of let's go and go. In short, I cannot recommend. You can take a look at it if it enters the bundle or something. Follow the curator for more game suggestions: ", "voted_up": false, "early_access": false}
