{"text": "\u2605\u2605 \u2606\u2606\u2606 Sorry to say, but Lost Planet 3 is really a mediocre game. Everything is characterized by mediocrity: from the plot, to the gunplay, to the level design, even the sound. I have read several reviews that have compared it to a \"cheap\" copy of Dead Space, and I am of the same opinion. It's not an exact copy, but it almost feels like Spark Unlimited (the developer) is just doing the homework swapping ideas from various famous TPSs here and there. Not that there is anything wrong with it, but the product that comes out is so flat that in a very short time it leads to boredom. The plot is very popular, with our standard model hero (male, white, family) having to do the same stuff for the first \u2153 of the game: get out of the RIG, shoot a couple of generic monsters, place the thermo column, fix the such broken stuff, etc ... From the middle onwards, the game worsens further by proposing a very long and very boring whole level, which would have the intent of creating anxiety in the player, but which on balance only ends up irritating him and compulsively pushing him to watch the orogiolo in the steam overlay, in the hope that the agony will end soon. Let's talk about the gameplay, the beating heart of the game: TREMENDO. Everything works badly, the cover system (solid in games like Gears of War) here proves to be a dancer, with the character often being exposed to enemy fire, or suddenly standing up and then crouching down. I found the fighting with the RIG quite unbearable: always the usual QTE instead of proposing a real fight. The graphics, the only element that raises the bar a little, is moved by the Unreal Engine 3, showing glimpses that are sometimes really convincing. Good snow / ice effect, as well as lighting effects. Sound to forget, the soundtrack that accompanies the game I would define inappropriate in some moments. I am aware of the amount of work that such a game requires, and I am sorry that Spark Unlimited came up with such a flat title. Basically I had the impression that they had carte blanche for the development of this third episode, the conditions for creating a nice plot and decent gameplay were there, instead they did nothing but develop yet another generic TPS standard to not to risk.. ", "voted_up": false, "early_access": false}
