{"text": "During my schooling, I was not very attentive in grammar class. I had no problem applying the rules instinctively but rather not feeling bored with these lessons. So don't talk to me about subjunctive, verb groups, indicative and whatnot, it just doesn't speak to me. However, do I have problems with writing? I think I'm doing pretty well (right?). Am I therefore the best person to evaluate this first opus of the trilogy \u201cThe Forest of Pago\u201d? Not necessarily, indeed. But here is my feeling. For this introduction, the game focuses on, I quote, the present indicative, the agreement between the conjugated verb and its subject, easily locate a conjugated verb in a sentence as well as its infinitive and its group, find easily the subject which corresponds to it, identify the people of the conjugation, learn the endings of the verbs of the three groups and the particular cases. The game is therefore intended mainly for students in CE1, CE2 (and you should manage to finish it in less than 1h30 if you are not a primary school student, I say that, I say nothing ...). In practice, the game is a succession of tables, more or less animated, where you follow Flora and her friends in search of the truth following the destruction of the village of Pago by a huge dragon. During 21 levels, you will have to read sentences and choose the correct answer among the three choices offered. In case of error, the game offers a little reminder of the rule to follow. After three errors, the level resets, however their short duration (I counted about 15 sentences per level) does not really penalize the player. It is a shame to note that the levels do not start with a lesson and that the reminders displayed in the event of an error are not clearer. The levels end with a summary but the game falls back into this trap of offering a fairly indigestible lesson, comparable to those in French books. You have to realize that the children who could play this game are also learning to read, but the instructions lack clarity and pedagogy (no color code, use of abbreviations, etc.). I would have liked a little more inventiveness on this point, otherwise what will be the motivation of the children to read it? To conclude, I am mixed on this game but I am obviously not the expected target. Children will probably have a lot more fun with this type of support than with their school books, but will they have the courage to read the lessons scattered throughout the chapters? Nothing is less sure. I would also mention some convoluted turns of phrase due to the strict use of the present tense for this first opus. A not always very wise choice. In addition, the price of the game is very high. Of course, it is understandable that the studio is remunerated and that the development of a game takes time, but on the parents' side 24.99 \u20ac is an expensive price paid for a game that can be completed in 1h30. I would like to be able to select a \"gray thumb\" for this evaluation, this option not being available I unfortunately have to make a choice. Do not hesitate to support Futurtech if their initiative interests you and to help the development of the second opus if the crowdfunding is set up by the studio. ", "voted_up": false, "early_access": false}
