{"text": "At the time of writing this, I have 55 hours in the game, yet I'm not recommending it, which might appear odd. I wish I could give it a thumb sideays, and if it's on sale for $5, it's worth a flyer, but the TLDR is that it's ultimately very mediocre. This is as close as a game is to Gran Turismo or GT Racing 2 on Steam, a quick and dirty simcade.  I'm a bit of a completionist, so I want to acquire every trophy there is to be acquired. This has made me spend dozens of hours in this title rather than in proper sim games, and they haven't been very fulfilling.  There are hundreds and hundreds of events, and while, in the base game, they are at least grouped somewhat logically, there is no sense of purpose of achievement. I almost feel like events were created at random, and finishing them doesn't really bring any joy or sense of achievement. The AI is a special beast. I've had to learn on which tracks to put it at medium and on which to put it on hard, because in time attack mode or on ovals, I crush the field mercilessly on medium, while on the hillclimb track I barely scrape by on the same difficulty level. This game offers the same tired old super sprint race formula: you start near the back of a 16-car grid, and you have to win a 3-lap race. The problem with this formula is that you cannot simultaneously have cars of roughly your level and also expect to make your way to the front of the field in this super short period of time. So, yeah, you need to feel excited about passing cars that aren't at your level, or you have to feel content with gaining only one or two places against challenging cars. The trouble is, the game isn't designed for the latter, and it won't net you the wins you need to progress through the career. The FFB on a steering wheel feels very mushy and unresponsive, almost boat-like. This isn't ideal, and for a simcade game I'm tempted to give Codies a pass on this, but given that Codemasters have provided much better FFB in some other titles, it's not like they don't have the technology, so it's a bit frustrating. I suppose this game is mostly designed for gamepad support, but still, it's a shortcoming. Don't expect anything close to realistic physics here. From drifting formula and LMP cars to every car feeling like a 10 ton brick when bumping against it, I feel like it's more of a feature than a bug, but it does make understanding the car far harder to achieve. The car selection is outstanding, and while they feel a bit more samey than I'd hope, I suppose that's more of a physics than car selection problem. Not only that, it's an absolutely gorgeous game; chasing sunsets and seeing rays hit a damp track is some of the prettiest stuff I've ever seen in a driving game. Still, to some it up, this game looks the part, but for everything else, it's just so-so. I've had fun with it, but I wish there was a superior simcade game with actual career progression. Project Cars 2 is the closest thing, though perhaps a bit too far on the sim side of the goldilocks zone for a simcade. ", "voted_up": false, "early_access": false}
