{"text": "It's amazing that for all my love for turn-based strategies in general, I somehow lost sight of it. However, a wave of enthusiastic reviews from gamers in the style of \"Worthy competitor\" and \"This should be new\" convinced to buy this miracle. The first hour was unforgettable, I squeaked like a thirteen-year-old girl from addictive gameplay, amazing graphics, thick atmosphere and dashing video sequences, hardly inferior to those of the numbered parts. After five hours of playing, you involuntarily begin to feel that something is wrong with it, and on the fifteenth you have a persistent feeling of cheating. Naturally, it does not stand up to any comparison either with or with, and if we also take into account the chic addons to them in the form of and, then the step-by-step spin-off of the series is perceived as an inferior fool cousin. All \"global management\" comes down to shmotizm, pumping fighters (by the way, pumping is implemented quite well for itself) and opening boxes with random gear and barrel attachments. Shmotism is presented at its worst: these boots give + 7% to evasion, and this helmet + 5% to accuracy. Do the developers really think that these pathetic bonuses can keep the interest in customizing fighters alive? I do not argue, sometimes among the legendary and epic things there are interesting examples, but this does not save the day. Yes, the bonuses cannot be called bold either, but there the weapon upgrade is one of dozens of global mechanics, and in it is the only \"entertainment\" outside the turn-based games. The main scourge is that this is a dummy project. The most delicious is dumped in the first hour and a half of the game, so that God forbid you do not have time to issue a refund. Then shameless self-copying begins. You don't have to go far for an example. Along with a couple of unique story missions and as many boss battles, there are four types of missions: in a certain number of moves, save two soldiers from captivity, collect a certain number of boxes until you are covered with bombardment, hold two points and, finally, clear the map to explode stocks of miraculous goo. These side quests are mandatory. And, apparently, they are so amazing that most of the already story missions are the same. Moreover, sometimes the modifiers of such side quests are completely absurd in their plot groundlessness. Soldiers, you need to hold these points, but for some reason you cannot use grenades, or, say, a couple of militiamen need to get blood from the nose out of the locust clutches, but the initial rescue squad will not consist of two broad-cheeked snouts, but for some reason only one ... While the games in the series offer a vast arsenal of various devices, it offers a fig. Here are two types of grenades: one heals, the other cripples, go fight. For the sake of decency, it was possible to introduce at least armor-piercing cartridges into the game. But it had potential. Here, fighters have the opportunity to perform as many as three actions per turn, and this can be at least three shots in a row. With such a gameplay skeleton, a very thoughtful tactic could turn out, but alas, you will not be full of bones without meat. You will not be full even on the strength of five completely indestructible locations. Sometimes developers play with the weather and time of day, but who are you trying to fool? Even in, which was criticized for a small number of cards, these cards were much larger, and they were much more diverse. Let's return to the absurdity of what is happening, the plot of the game persistently tries to convince us that every fighter is worth its weight in gold. In fact, we are forced to go through most of the missions for the warrior-heroes, and the vegetating nouns very soon begin to lag behind in the level. What does the game offer? Complete the side mission and save new no-names with the current level! And in order for them to have enough space in the detachment, they will have to dismiss the yellow-horned characters who cannot keep up with the heroes. And we do a similar feint every hour. Elegant, however. In this situation, I was more worried about the fate of the nameless tankette from than the local resistance fighter. Having stuffed the giant creature with lead at the end of the second act, I realized with annoyance that there was nothing in it that could keep me for another ten hours of monotonous routine. ", "voted_up": false, "early_access": false}
