{"text": "Walking simulator is not my favorite genre, far from it, but from time to time something that catches my eye appears. In fact, The Town of Light's story is great, causing curiosity and agony as we explore the old asylum, making us constantly question what is real and what is insanity, who we are controlling and even who the story really talks about. Audio is also a positive part. The soundtrack leaves us tense and distressed, even though the gameplay does not show jump scare. The experience is totally psychological, according to the theme of the game. The dubbing does not change the tone and serves to immerse us in the story according to the emotions that the protagonist's voice actress wanted to pass, making us pay attention to each line of dialogue. Perhaps you are wondering \"why a walk simulator, which does the main part that the genre needs well, won a No Recommend? Below ... As soon as we take control of the character, the first problem arises: the Engine. Unity it\u2019s not a good engine or it\u2019s not well used on the PC, because generally the technical part always has problems in practically all the games that use it. In The Town of Light, the big flaw is the absurdly constant and heavy stutter, no matter if is running at 60 or 90 fps. A very annoying problem that hinders the experience, even though there are ways to mitigate it, but it will always be there, no matter the quality of the machine, a driver or Windows. The fact that the problem exists forces you to leave the game to look for solutions on the internet, things that take time and a lot of patience. If well configured it is not a heavy game and it is possible to run at high frame rates, but when looking at HWINFO data after a two-hour game without interruption, note how much it consumes from the machine, mainly (but not only) in Ultra. This is limited to 60 frames per second, otherwise it would be natural to consume as much as possible. It is a problem because The Town of Light does not have beautiful graphics, the animations are terrible and there are few dynamic objects in the scenarios, not justifying the intensive use of the PC. I am not going to pass the cloth because it is an indie product, because another walk simulator called The Vanishing of Ethan Carter is beautiful, very optimized and also independent, but uses Unreal Engine 3 in a masterful way. For this reason, it is difficult to understand why this producer chose Unity, much less when it is noticed the polishing that it did not do, including the launch of patches. Finally, despite encouraging replay with the aim of unlocking different sides of certain chapters, perhaps changing the ending, I didn't feel like playing again. Redoing everything for small discoveries and changes is not encouraging, even though it is a very small campaign. If exploration was interesting, that is, more than walking aimlessly to find reading papers or achievements to unlock, it would certainly be worth it. As it is not the case, it is not worth the trouble. NOTE: although many complain about the walking speed of the character, I found the measure. Certainly a slower movement makes the player pay more attention to the setting and history, providing a better benefit to the genre. ", "voted_up": false, "early_access": false}
