{"text": "Imagine performing surgery within a claw-crane toy vending machine.  The surgeon's single hand is, by design, one of the clumsiest manifestations of inter-activity ever published.  Of course this would be the very point and what makes it so much fun! The difficulty in getting anywhere because of this intentional disconnect with user input can, however, be frustrating at times.  I personally require a mouse pad the size of Central Park in order to move the arm around (even on the highest sensitivity).  It's definitely presented as a joke game, not an achievement or skill game, although those things are very much required to get anywhere.  There is no advice or direction in how to approach a given surgery, lots of bloody fun in the trial and error.  Too difficult to grasp objects in general, it can take an eon to get the scalpel in your hand at the right angle for incision.  Certainly not realisitic, and the title \"simulator\" here must be taken with a grain of salt.  Or a salt mine even.          On the positive, I totally knew what I was getting into and got a deal on the game anyway, so it's no travesty that's happened here.  The game really is pretty funny, and that seems to be it's greatest achievement.  I had  dreams of a more balanced mix of sim and parody...but got mostly the latter.            If  the hand were SLIGHTLY more dexterous, I would've enjoyed it more.  I'm sure it must be rewarding for true mouse-keteers that eventually hone their precision with the movements... that seems the only way to advance passed the first surgery even.  When the difficulty in progressing becomes more frustrating than fun, a game generally loses me. ", "voted_up": false, "early_access": false}
