{"text": "Well, it's a game where a UNICEF commercial appears to put stickers on you and ask you to collaborate. You, who move on from the topic, look to get away, grab a catalog of El Corte Ingl\u00e9s toys to throw it at him and take advantage of the confusion to disappear, but against all odds, the catalog explodes releasing a lot of ghosts that will chase you through a lot of identical corridors each other. The only way to reverse the problem will be to put together all the pages of the toy catalog looking for them through the web of corridors and rooms in a macabre game of boredom and despair. A search where your success will be measured by how lucky you are to find the damn pages, because it is impossible to reason and reach logical conclusions about where they are. We could say that \"The Hat Man: Shadow Ward\" is a game of running through a maze without getting caught looking for pages of a random book. The game has some element of adventure, but testimonial. Every now and then you pick up an item to use it almost instantly. It is more of a crappy place where when the UNICEF commercial catches you, it makes you the file and you have to go down. So, you start over a good chunk back, when the game autosaved (no, you can't save the game whenever you feel like it). The experience was abhorrent and I got fed up with the game really quickly, so I uninstalled it. When I thought the nightmare was over, I sat on the sofa at home to reflect on quantum physics when I saw a catalog of toys on the floor, on the carpet. A chill ran down my spine. I felt like the fucking damn catalog of the game had haunted me to reality to make me suffer with its shit, but luckily, I noticed and it was only a catalog of toys from Alcampo. ", "voted_up": false, "early_access": false}
