{"text": "A simple, mechanically, reaction game. The bottom line is as follows: The player controls the arrow, which flies at great speed along the track, on which obstacles periodically arise. The arrow must dodge obstacles by moving to adjacent tracks. Good thing - each level adds new mechanics. At the same time, the mechanics, although simple, add additional complexity (in a good way) to the game. However, right there it is worth mentioning that there are only 7 levels. The picture is pleasant, albeit minimalistic. It also poses a serious danger to epileptics. Music, although at first seems pretty good and driving, but very quickly becomes boring. Plus, due to some gameplay features associated with a slight acceleration / deceleration of time, it soon starts to seriously cringe from it. There are several game design issues with the game that make the game feel like it's not always fair, which shouldn't be the case in a hardcore reaction game. The player must always clearly understand that it is he who is to blame for the loss, and not the game. Problem # 1: Delay between entering commands when moving between tracks. After accepting a command to move to an adjacent track, the arrow cannot be immediately sent to the next adjacent track. There is a small gap in command entry. It feels like the game needs to complete its movement animation. Although the animation is short, at the speed of the game, even a fraction of a second is a criminal lot. Problem # 2: Tilting the camera towards special obstacles. We have to admit that this problem grows from the quite correct idea that the player should be very clear about what exactly is required of him now. In the game, gradually, special obstacles appear: Blue, which need to be flown only from a certain direction, and green, which do not need to be flown. The camera always clearly shows a new special obstacle so that the player can always see it. However, the problem here is the speeds at which this game takes place. Because of them, such sudden camera turns very much disorient the player. Problem # 4. Excessive feedback. There are several events in the game that are accompanied by feedback - an increase in the speed of the track, and the destruction of the enemy by the player. Basically, as in the case of the last paragraph, the roots of this problem grow from the correct idea that the player must be very clear about what exactly happened. And, in principle, the game copes with this. But there is a nuance. The fact is that as soon as one of these events occurs, time slows down for a split second. And in some situations, this is quite enough to get off the usual rhythm and jump to the next lane too early, which often leads to a collision. Also, another gameplay problem is associated with this feedback - the fact is that the control at this moment is blocked for the same fraction of a second, which is why the player also periodically gets out of rhythm. To summarize, I can neither advise this, nor, on the contrary, refuse the recommendation. This negative analysis should be rather neutral, but Steam does not provide such an opportunity. For those who want to kill some time in a hardcore arcade game for reactions, it is suitable. But you need to be prepared for the fact that she may not seem entirely honest. ", "voted_up": false, "early_access": false}
