{"text": "\"Push The Crate\" was clearly inspired by the classic \"Sokoban\". But instead of having to move boxes to the correct position in a warehouse as a warehouse worker, you play a gentleman dressed in medieval clothes who has to move boxes to certain fields in a clearing in an area closed by fences. Since the game can be controlled from a classic bird's eye view but also from the so-called \"3rd person\" perspective, it looks very modern and gives the impression of great graphics in the main menu. But some things don't look good to look at, especially from a bird's eye view: The lighting is too bright even at the highest graphics setting, shadows look unrealistic and the textures look very blurry. But graphics aren't everything; For me personally, besides having fun, the soundscape and background music is more important. The game can score a lot with atmospheric background noise and several medieval music. The music is chosen randomly at each level so that you don't always have to listen to the same music. It is controlled using the a, s, w, d keys, although unfortunately you cannot use the arrow keys as an alternative or even change the key assignment. This is a big flaw because I personally prefer to use the arrow keys. Unfortunately, the game also has deficits in the most important aspect: Moving the boxes is very error-prone and inaccurate. Sometimes a little nudge moves the box one field further and another time it rushes to the nearest fence. If you are unlucky and that is often the case in this regard, the box even ends up on the other side of the fence and is therefore no longer accessible. Due to these circumstances, solving the level is a pure game of chance and you often have to start it again. It is extremely frustrating when you think you have found the solution to a level, but it is difficult or impossible to put into practice because of the faulty box movements. (One wonders why this was not noticed during testing! After all, this error can appear in the first level!) At the end it should be said that even the achievements are not free from errors: While some can be unlocked quite normally, you get some without having fulfilled the requirements or vice versa, despite the achievement of the requirement the achievement remains open. In short: A \"Sokoban\" implementation that seems very promising at first glance disappoints in particular with unnecessary errors and a lack of free key assignment, which in the end only brings frustration instead of fun and in no way justifies a purchase without rework. ", "voted_up": false, "early_access": false}
